desc: TP53, a tumor suppressor in the DNA damage pathway, is the most frequently mutated gene in cancer.

TP53 encodes the p53 tumor suppressor protein, a transcription factor that responds to cellular stresses, including DNA damage and oncogenic activation, by inducing downstream anti-tumor responses such as DNA repair and apoptosis (PMID: 11099028). TP53 is the most commonly mutated gene in human cancers, and germline mutations occur in the cancer predisposition syndrome Li-Fraumeni (PMID: 22713868, 21765642). The p53 protein consists of an N-terminal transactivation domain, a central DNA-binding domain, an oligomerization domain and a C-terminal regulatory domain (PMID: 22713868).
